def: A gutter or channel for water, hewn out of the bottom of aworking drift. Page.
Without wit; stupid. [Obs.]Think'st thou I am so shallow, so conceitless. To be seduced by thyflattery Shak.
An umbelliferous herb (Meum Athamanticum) having finely dividedleaves, common in Europe; -- called also baldmoney, mew, andbearwort. [Written also spignel.]
The quality of being extensible; the capacity of beingextended; as, the extensibility of a fiber, or of a plate of metal.
Copied, reproduced as a molding or cast, in contradistinctionfrom the original model.
Having the edge or extremity bordered by filiform processesthicker than hairs; fringed; as, the fimbriate petals of the pink;the fimbriate end of the Fallopian tube.
A subscript mark, number, or letter. See Subscript, a.
Incapable of having a peer, or equal.
